# ATLAS environment configuration template.
#
# Copy this file to `.env` (gitignored) in the repo root and fill in real
# values there. NEVER commit a real `.env` file or paste a real API key into
# this template — `.env.example` must only ever contain variable names and
# `env:VAR` reference syntax, never an actual secret value.
#
# PORT AUTHORITY NOTE (read this before touching ~/.atlas/config.yaml):
# `~/.atlas/config.yaml`'s `gateway.rust_port` / `cockpit.port` fields are
# informational only and are NOT read by `atlas up` today — nothing wires
# them into the actual spawn command. The environment variables below
# (ATLAS_GATEWAY_PORT / ATLAS_GATEWAY_URL / ATLAS_COCKPIT_URL) are
# authoritative for the gateway/cockpit spawn + health-check URLs that
# `gateway_control.py` / `cockpit_control.py` actually use. If you change a
# port, change it here — editing config.yaml alone will not take effect.

# --- Provider -----------------------------------------------------------
# ATLAS never stores a literal API key in config. The provider's api_key
# field is always an "env:VAR_NAME" reference; set the real secret in your
# shell environment or in this gitignored .env file, under the variable
# name your reference points at. Example reference variable name below —
# set your key here, never commit it.
ATLAS_PROVIDER_API_KEY_REF=env:ATLAS_PROVIDER_API_KEY
# ATLAS_PROVIDER_API_KEY=

# --- Gateway -------------------------------------------------------------
ATLAS_GATEWAY_PORT=8484
ATLAS_GATEWAY_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8484

# --- Cockpit ---------------------------------------------------------------
ATLAS_COCKPIT_URL=http://127.0.0.1:5173

# --- Database / state home --------------------------------------------------
# Left blank: defaults to ~/.atlas (config.yaml, atlas.db, wiki/, pid files).
# Set only if you want ATLAS state isolated to a non-default directory.
ATLAS_HOME=
